{
  "title": "Tiri Environmental Conservation Project",
  "transcript": "Right, so my name's David Mitchell and I'm the head of the Tiri Environmental Conservation project.[cite: 1] The project was set up in 1998 by a team of five environmental experts at the University of Auckland.[cite: 1] The aim of Tiri was to address the most pressing environmental problems across the whole of New Zealand and look for solutions.[cite: 1] There is a problem that large parts of the coastline have disappeared at an alarmingly rapid rate, while there is also a threat to marine life from water pollution.[cite: 1] There are currently a number of projects we're working on, and we're looking at different ways people can contribute.[cite: 1] One thing volunteers are encouraged to do is to take people around and visit our conservation areas.[cite: 1] The tourist areas are restricted as we try to limit the human activities which may cause more damage.[cite: 1] It's a big concern for us, and we work very hard to ensure the wildlife and natural habitats in these areas are protected.[cite: 1] A lot of people ask questions about the Tiri project, and are interested in finding out about what we do.[cite: 1] It's actually very easy to join Tiri.[cite: 1]",
